author: @rodneylockwood1362
processed_text: It is good that they capture the experience of coming home for veterans and the struggle of trying to assimilate back into society. For me, the hardest part was not being in combat in Iraq and Afghanistan, rather the bigger struggle was coming back home.¬†From 2006 to 2010 I served in combat every one of those years, so when they decided to downsize the Marine Corps I was let go, thus taking away my power base of my brothers that served with me during that time. I was at a loss, because being with them was very therapeutic for me. A part of me wanted to stay in because they were there, and another part of me wanted to get out because I didn't want my combat experiences to be the sole defining portion of my life. Most days after getting out I would lock myself indoors staring at the world outside. I did everything from changing my appearance to how I acted to hide the fact that I was even in the service. If I was out, I would put a brave face on, but I was still there. My destructiveness was not from turning to drugs or alcohol, rather it was from me hiding myself from society. Only close friends and family knew that I was in, but they don't and probably won't know the whole story of being in Iraq and Afghanistan. I was at a loss.Lately seeing how America takes on issues made me change the way I saw myself. We treat America as one big soap opera and tend to focus on problems rather than solutions. Around late 2013 my life had come to a full circle, I began to focus on solutions. The solution for me was to ask myself what I was passionate about, what was my driving force in life, and why did it have to leave. That passion and driving force in my life is helping those in need. It is the reason why I joined the Marine Corps. Whether it be a smile, a hello, to helping the homeless in my community helped put that purpose back in my life. ¬†Guillermo Cervera has it right. Americans are more individualistic rather than collectivist which is why there is a struggle with returning vets. The military is a collectivist society. We eat, sleep, work, fight, sweat, bleed, cry, and have lived with the most primitive of needs together with the one common goal; the survival of the pack. When we see Americans with a "what's in it for me" mentality it pushes us back with no relation to our society and trying to live those collectivist ideals we have learned in combat.22 veterans are committing suicide each day. Out of a population of roughly 314 million Americans in which around .005% or roughly 1.6 million who are veterans of Iraq and Afghanistan makes this suicide rate a tragedy and an epidemic. Getting the word out with documentaries like these will help Americans see. Most of us who have served are not looking for a thank you or any sympathy, rather it is the understanding that counts.Thank you to Brendan O'Byrne, Guillermo Cervera, Sebastian Junger, and the production crew on getting the word out and making the picture a bit more clearer. ¬† ¬† ¬† ¬† ¬†

author: @StevenKnightArrowood
processed_text: Do "natural"/organic molecules/compounds process/decay in more "natural"/organic ways in comparison to artificial/synthetic substances polluting/disrupting the balance of nature by being too potent or abnormal to the standard bonding processes? This question is in reference to both human internal processing as well as external processing(decay). Which is more efficient at being processed through its cycle and also efficient at serving its purpose?¬† ¬† ¬† ¬† I did appreciate the logic in your argument about making decisions based on more relevant data (relative to the situation), like whether the substance is objectively good/bad for you & the environment, how it's being used, & in what quantities, how effective/efficient at serving its purpose, as well as what will happen to it after its purpose is fulfilled.¬† ¬† ¬† ¬†Actually, reminds me of the book "Cradle to Cradle: Remaking the Way We Make Things", by Michael Braungart & William McDonough, which (among other things) speaks of how there are 2 metabolisms on the planet. There is the Biological metabolism, which refers to all the natural cycles and natural resources (things consumed by microorganisms), and there is the Technical metabolism, which refers to industrial processed compounds & synthetic compounds which should be designed to be upcycled back into the human industrial system much more efficiently than attempting to dilute it into the Biological metabolism.I could go on about how I disagree with Theodore Gray's feelings about the differences between the App Store & the Google Play Store and my belief that the Touchpress apps would sell well on the Android platform, but I will end my comment here.¬†

author: @polyglotdreams
processed_text: A lot of what you say is useful. Nevertheless, you often preface some of your beliefs with "research shows" .... but in a number of cases what you present as conclusive is actually not so ... for example, the idea that our "consciousness is just a snowball on top of our unconscious". I would suggest you do much more research.In particular, the research on ‚Äúattention & automaticity‚Äù has gone through many phases.¬†‚ÄúSnowball on the iceberg‚Äù was proposed by Tim Wilson in his book ‚ÄúStrangers to Ourselves.‚Äù There is no evidence for this wild claim!¬†This outlook is associated with Bargh‚Äôs claim that social behavior is almost completely automatic. It seems very strange that you would support such a belief since your goal seems to be to get people to recognize their ‚Äúbiases‚Äù (code for automatic processing) by examining and the beliefs that modulate this process. In order to do so, it takes recognizing that share of conscious processing can play a significant role in social interaction.Using methods of opposition in conscious and automatic processing experimentation allows for greater measurement of components in spontaneous trait inferences. Uleman et al. (2005) demonstrate that conscious processing are often roughly evenly balanced in conditions in which time is not severely curtailed for decision making. Also, Payne (2005) shows that the only time automatic processing dominates in ‚Äúweapon-bias experiments‚Äù takes place is when the response must be within 500 msec.Gladwell also tries to over argue for an exaggerated role of automatic decision making in his book, which unfortunately also exaggerates the ‚Äúautomaticity juggernaut.‚Äù¬†I have watched more of your video and I see that you do believe in the power of mindfulness and advocate developing the practice of mindfulness. Great, then please consider getting rid of some of your arguments that are unsupported since for those who are familiar with the multiple aspects of the study of consciousness it is a big ‚Äúturnoff‚Äù. In particular, I am referring to the ‚Äúsnowball on the iceberg‚Äù view of conscious/unconscious (subconscious or automaticity) dichotomy.Your focus on awareness of priming as well as on what you call ‚Äúsystems and structure‚Äù is also very useful.¬†One final comment is that you might want to consider the benefits of becoming multilingual and multicultural. The process can greatly increase awareness of our thought processes.

processed_text: With all due respect to the speaker, he vastly underestimates just how much science can test and explain, and much of what he claims is the domain of spirituality is really just gaps in his knowledge of science. ¬†Approaches like game theory and evolutionary psychology already explains why we have the kinds of ethics and morality that we do. ¬†He conflates uncertainty within decision-making - whether to steal or kill, by his examples - with uncertainty about decision-making - as in we don't know how to approach the problem. ¬†There's natural uncertainty about stealing and killing because we do not have the ability to fully predict the consequences of our actions, but that doesn't mean we don't have the ability to weigh the costs and benefits that we can foresee. ¬†And if it's uncertainty we're worried about, I trust statistics to deal with it more reliably than spirituality.

processed_text: Evolution is nothing at all like an observed fact. Tell us one thing you know to be true about it? For example, a fallacious example was given, among the replies here, that evolution had predicted "genetic media" which is pure made up nonsense. Darwin thought that the human cell was literally a glob of jelly. He would've been the very first to have pared his theory down to adaptation -at most- if he had had any idea what awaited science in DNA. author: @jknight1914
processed_text: Martin Clausen¬†This review by Bradley T. Lepper is heavy on the ad hominem, (not to mention the familiarly contemptuous tone of threatened consensus), but also disappointingly thin as a persuasive refutation of Cremo's evidence. This makes me think that charging Cremo with being ‚Äòideologically motivated‚Äô is a case of the pot calling the kettle black. There‚Äôs not very much of substance amidst all the invective and charges of 'ignorance' and 'absurdity' to respond to here.¬†Lepper‚Äôs bias is clear when he writes:‚ÄúThe authors are critical of archaeologists for rejecting the very early radiometric dates for technologically recent stone artifacts at Hueyatlaco, Mexico (pp. 91-93), but they are as quick to reject radiometric dates which do not agree with their preconceived interpretations (pp. 125, 139-140).‚ÄùThis is a misleading statement. According to Steen-MacIntyre, the geological evidence, let alone¬†the¬†radiometric dating, is ‚Äòclear cut‚Äô for the Mexican artifacts. The four dating methods used were much more reliable than the examples cited on pages 125 & 139-140. Cremo therefore has sound scientific reasons for rejecting this earlier¬†radiometric data as it was collected decades¬†before when the science was still in its infancy and prone to inaccuracy. Hardly a controversial position.¬†Was Lepper simply mistaken here or being willfully dishonest? Either way, I think his bias is clear. In fact it leaps off the page. ¬†

author: @jknight1914
processed_text: Ross Bagley¬†"the fault is that he looks for odd cases that are poorly explained or could have alternative explanations and uses those to justify a post-hoc explanation for human evolution that matches up with his religion's creation myth."This is not the case with the Mexican evidence mentioned previously. This contains a range of consistently correlated data. Nothing ambiguous about it and not much that is "odd or poorly explained".¬†"In science, you don't start from your conclusion and then cherrypick evidence that might support it."This is exactly what Cremo argues happened after Darwin's The Descent of Man of 1871, which postulated a theory for human evolution, and which paleoanthropology then set out to prove correct. After 1871, ancient hominid skeletons were placed in an evolutionary context, even if the evidence suggested otherwise.¬†"To assert a credible alternative, you start with why your explanation also explains the vast majority of observations and then show that your explanation does a better job with one of more classes of oddball cases that are not explained by the current "accepted" explanation."If the theory is that all crows are black, does finding one white crow overturn the theory or modify it? It may not be a question of an "alternative", but a modification of what we already know.¬†"...his proposal fails to explain the vast majority of observations that point to gradual evolution of humanity by natural processes over a long period of time..."Is this really what the record points to? Have you seen the evidence? If there were as you claim, a "gradual evolution", then "The Missing Link" Holy Grail of paleoanthropology would certainly have been found by now. They've been looking in all the right places to find evidence supporting Darwin's hypothesis for almost 150 years . Since they started hunting in the 1870s, Darwin's theory has settled into a dogmatic assumption. How much longer will you give them before you start to wonder if it's the wrong theory?¬†

processed_text: The problem with Pareto's idea of when to make a change in law or public policy is that the system of law in place in every society rests on centuries-long entrenched privilege. Just requires and end to privilege, the most serious form of which is landed privilege (i.e., the privatization of rent). As Winston Churchill declared when campaigning for the House of Commons in 1909, the most serious problem in the British Isles was monopoly privilege. He then declared that land monopoly is the "mother of all monopolies."

author: @RaviAnnaswamy
processed_text: First of all, great talk stretching the mind to think through far more deeply.What I observed was the strength of his argument is not how likely the superintelligence-turning-rogue but how severe, sudden, uncontrollable it could be, so we better prepare for it.To that end, every time a questioner questions the assumption he hurriedly and very cleverly quickly sheds aside that question and pursues full steam the 'threat'. Take my following note as a genunine complement - he reminded me the tone of my mother who got us all to do homework by scaring us without scolding or shouting. She would just not smile but keep saying - 'oh, those who dont study have to find a job like begging' (not her exact words, just giving you an idea..) and whenever we suspected what she is saying she would sidestep it to bring on this and that to distract us into working hard. One day humanity may thank Nick for doing something very similar - instead of getting distracted by the (low-right-now) probability of a catastrophe he wants to us to minimize the severity if (and when) it happensHe is like the engineer who had the wisdom to tame combustion by containing it into a chamber, before putting it onto a cart with smooth shiny wheels.BTW, his Simulation Argument (search youtube) scared me and held my thought captive for a week or two! author: @sckchui
processed_text: An intelligent entity would recognise the limits of its own intelligence and the need to prepare for the unanticipated. ¬†Just as intelligent humans are concerned that resource depletion and loss of biodiversity are actions that will ultimately impoverish our future selves and our descendants, so will the superintelligent be reluctant to impoverish themselves with similar actions. ¬†Just as intelligent humans nurture and embrace diversity as a source of new and useful ideas and perspectives, so will the superintelligent seek to enhance diversity for its own benefit. ¬†Fighting over resources on Earth will be absurd when it becomes trivial for the superintelligent to expand to the stars. ¬†Greed, fear, pride, bigotry - these are the responses of the stupid to problems they can't solve; the superintelligent will, by definition, have no need for these.

author: @ConQuiX1
processed_text: This is the argument I tend to favour as well. I can imagine the scenarios Nick is envisioning, but I don't think they are terribly likely because they are so tangential to the evolutionary algorithm that is bringing them about. Why would a super intelligent entity be satisfied with making paperclips or accomplishing any singular task. Even if we find great interests in our lives, and are ultimately concerned with progress and scientific discovery, we don't just do that, and I have a hard time that the paperclip making machine would be a stable state for any self-aware entity. Once you are actually aware of yourself and the world around you enough to be a threat to humans, you presumably can reflect on your own behaviour and ascribe meaning to things. The risk is in whether it will value the things in the way we do.For instance, I think we might have to worry about the inevitable time where we may be forced to save on space and energy and move our entire biosphere into the digital simulation (very much like the matrix, but perhaps with many of them and for basically everything). All the physical matter would then be devoted to information processing. I think we are going to eventually want to do this anyway if for no other reason that preserving the history of the development of our planet beyond the lifetime of our sun. The question is whether a machine intelligence would just sort of impersonally decide to start that process early and / or take choices away from humans who may wish to self-determine in alternative ways. Some humans (and possibly even dolphins or chimps (etc.) may want to have their intelligence enhanced and others may wish to remain as they are (or they may decide to do it at a later time). My concern would be that we allow as much freedom to individuals as we safely can - but for how long can we justify this approach for the sake of efficiency?A super intelligent AI may see the distant future and the probability / utility of avoiding heat death, and either care about this or not. It may make subsequently better estimates based on improved understandings of physics and present circumstances that would cause it to make these decisions early - and we may have no rational argument against it. Whether we enter this debate with AI or not, intelligent agents of the future will be locked in successive debates about whether to enjoy the time and resources we have, or risk some or all percentage of our processing power on working out a way to survive heat death. This is a very difficult problem - it's the ultimately long term thinking question, and we don't yet know enough about physics to conclude survival of heat-death in someway.Off the cuff, making a new big-bang (perhaps with a newer and better optimized values for dark energy and certain other constants) seems a more likely possibility than somehow beating the 2nd law (which seems like the most implausible scenario I can think of practically by definition). Granted, this is a pretty crazy scenario, but we may face some kind of terrible choice - we may have to either effectively (by devoting processing resources to it) or directly (by destroying ourselves) have to cut our lives shorter in order to ensure that some form of life is able to persist beyond the heat-death of our own universe. The trouble is that we won't know for certain if the baby universe will manifest the desired results, and we'll only be able to run elaborate models of this process (and I think there's a law from Turing or Godel that places limits on how accurately we can model the new universe within our own universe).So in other words, we can decide to enjoy the time we have fully - and because of the accelerating expansion, we will face a very slow and grueling drop off in our collective and eventually individual intelligence as our universe spreads out until the point of the cessation of all cognition - OR we can devote ourselves fully to solving the heat-death problem. It seems to me that super intelligence or not, the nature of this problem makes it exceedingly difficult - it's a moral question for which the superintelligence can have no definitive answer, and cannot model the outcome with perfect accuracy. The only real hope for settling this question would be the worst scenario of all - that something about the nature of physics and our universe convincingly and definitively rules out the possibility of life in our universe surviving heat-death by any means. On the bright side, if we could do that early on, it would at least allow us to fully enjoy the time we have - but perhaps we all face our own versions of this kind of problem already.

author: @ConQuiX1
processed_text: Cid - the range of possibilities for machine intelligence wholly contains the possibilities for organic intelligence in principle. That is to say that the possibilities for synthetic entities are at least as great - they could be very much like us, or something else that we haven't considered possible. The way I reached this conclusion is that synthetic intelligence - in principle (an important distinction) - has the full range of tools that biological intelligence has, plus - any other new degrees of freedom that we / it can unlock by being or becoming more hardware agnostic. I mean this is is just another way to recognize the direction we are headed in from a large scale evolutionary perspective. We won't change substrates unless there are demonstrable improvements to be had. Swapping much of our biology for more robust systems with more options for subsequent improvement, maintenance, upkeep and alternate energy sources with the possibility of surviving the harsh climate of space or the ocean depths is a no brainer. The moment we figure out how to navigate this transition in a way that preserves what we care about - we are all gonna make that switch as fast as our tech of the time permits. So the AI will evolve and we will evolve, because if we make it to that point - we will be them.As for the heat death problem, merging with the vacuum of space is what we already do - that's what death is to my ear, and if you want to pull a Deepak and argue that it's not, the burden is on you to unpack the relevant physics, demonstrate it, and make a compelling argument for the possibility of consciousness existing in that state. Needless to say, if you manage to pull any of that off within the next decade or so, all the theists and new agers will be breaking down your door for speaking engagements, autographs of your book, and perhaps other favours as well best left unspecified. For the escape to another realm, we better have a way to learn about that universe and look before we leap. Similarly to the joining the vacuum merge, there's no reason to think this is physically possible. Granted, the baby universe might not be either, but at least we have one big bang that we know about, and if nature can do it - and we are a part of her, perhaps we can discover how to do it too, but it seems probable that we won't be able to join it from our outer bubble... (To be clear - I don't think nature is conscious - let alone female, figure of speech! ;)

author: @sckchui
processed_text: *****¬†Greed and fear are emotional responses to uncertainty: greed is the stockpiling of resources against possible future deprivation, fear is the triggering of emergency panic responses against perceived imminent threats. ¬†The "superintelligent", if they are to qualify as such, will have far greater capability to accurately foresee possible future events, thus experience far less uncertainty. ¬†You don't fear things you understand and know how to deal with.Pride is a sense of self worth, and while the superintelligent will no doubt be capable of calculating their self worth, by definition they will be unlikely have an inflated or unjustified sense of self worth, because that is by definition a miscalculation of self worth, and the superintelligent will be unlikely to miscalculate.Bigotry and prejudice is forming opinions about individuals based on crude generalisations rather than precise details, and is a symptom of ignorance, of a lack of detailed knowledge. ¬†The superintelligent, by definition, will be less ignorant, thus be less prone to bigotry and prejudice.Humans are not as far more intelligent than other animals as you imagine, and even within our own species the range of intelligence is quite remarkable. ¬†But look at examples of the most intelligent among use, people like Einstein or Newton, and ask yourself: were they greedy, constantly fearful, conceited, and bigoted? ¬†No. ¬†Far more likely for them to suffer at the hands of the more numerous and less intelligent: Socrates, poisoned for criticising the Athenian government; Galileo, imprisoned for daring to say the Earth revolved around the Sun; Turing, castrated for homosexuality despite being instrumental in defeating Nazi cyphers; Einstein, driven from his home by the Nazis for being Jewish. ¬†So often the intelligent are accused of being a threat to society, but history proves them right. ¬†Now we're talking about the "superintelligent", entities whose intelligences will tower above even Einstein, and people fear them because that's what people do when they don't understand.

author: @MarkoKraguljac
processed_text: There is a tendency to overestimate, over-dramatize and over-anthropomorphize coming strong AI entities. Thats because we find very hard to imagine (and separate) anything "smarter" than us from concept of god or absolute. The moment we hear something is "smarter", reptilian parts of our brains start projecting, imagining and fear mongering. Thats our evolutionary baggage. In my opinion, probable medium term reality is about intelligence that will assist us in optimizing solutions to very concrete problems. Like farm layouts, road network optimizations, material design and testing, medical research, product and production line design etc. We point to a problem and get a set of different solutions based on changing parameters. We need intelligence that will do all the hard/boring stuff. I, for one, dont need computer to be my friend (which could make it potentially dangerous) but to release me from being a paid slave in a economy based on confusion, manipulation, violence and hype. It should and will work just as ordinary calculators work today, it "goes off" the moment it solves what we need be solved.

processed_text: Honestly he misses the point when it comes to trolling.¬† This fixation on trolling is a distraction tactic used by so many, its overblown.¬† You only have to look at the current Gamergate fiasco affecting the games media, where wide spread corruption and even journolist type secret mailing lists have been uncovered where these people work behind the scenes to perpetuate false narratives for their own self interest.¬† These people use the narrative of victimhood, of trolling to brow beat their opponents into silence.¬† Its such an effective and attractive tactics its been taken up by so many people with malevolent intent, even regimes.¬†¬†¬† I'm sure some of the stated reasons behind controls on the internet in places like china or russia or iran are to "protect" the people from trolls.¬† The definition of troll has crept over time to really just mean people who dare disagree with me.I just see one problem is being far worse than another, sure there are some psychopaths out there, but they are a super minority, while people who have various agendas have latched onto this issue as an excuse to game the system for their own advantage, whether its silencing dissent or to smear ideological opponents en mass.¬† Just look at sites which claim to control speech to combat trolling.¬† Any valid dissent with proof like urls or just arguments the author can't deal with will stay in the pending queue forever.¬† The excuse of controlling trolls leads to suppression of dissent. Again, look up the gamergate scandal, the only sites willing to cover this are the breitbarts of the world, while a wall of silence exists in the regular gaming media, the mainstream media only echos the games media being too lazy to research for themselves, which only reinforces the narrative and corrupts places like wikipedia who use them as "authoritative sources", and the narrative of "trolling" and victimhood just continue to rule the day.The missing part of the "trend" is that people are more and more willing to act as victims for advantage.¬† Not just online but in real life.¬† A prominent feminist blogger resorted to making threats against herself when she couldn't find what she needed on the site she was going after, she's being prosecuted last I checked, meg lankers simmons was her name.¬†¬† A lesbian waitress¬† famously made national news when she claimed her patrons had left a bigoted message on her tip receipt when in fact that was not true.¬† She got sympathy, coverage and donations, and when caught didn't give it back.¬† A family claimed their disfigured daughter was kicked out of a KFC, turns out they were lying about that too. They too received donations.¬† That is the actual trend, not one of impulsive trolling, its more of one of impulsive victimhood and a need to believe in such stories.

author: @sjgcoe
processed_text: Personally, I think this issue is a lot more black and white than seems to have come across to me. Freedom of any kind, not only freedom of speech does indeed come with a price. That price is a spectrum of many things but one of the most important is respect for others. Having the right to say whatever you want does not give you the right to abuse others in any way. People who say such horrendous and abusive things should pay the price of their actions and lose the freedom of speech, especially as they didn't even earn it in the first place. It is a gift that has been given to us by previous generations. I strongly believe there has to be consequences for actions otherwise there is no education and if there is no education there is only ignorance and ignorance leads to such abuse. If the likes of google, youtube etc etc clamped down on such things it would have a massive impact on showing people such behaviour is unacceptable. A quote comes to mind and I take this from an ethical and moral point not a religious 'evil wins when good people do nothing.' This is why what Lauren and the band have done is so important as it stands up for saying no to such abuse and more people need to do likewise. It especially needs to happen from those in power who have a responsibility to make sure freedom isn't misinterpreted as a freedom to hurt others. That is not what freedom is. They need to focus more on protecting people and worry less about losing some trolls who have no right to claim they deserve freedom of speech when they never earned it or are too ignorant to understand the consequences of such behaviour.

But we have to say something.""There's so much chatter and discussion around mindfulness that we can miss out on the thing we sought to discover in the first place.""to study the science of compassion so that when we take these practices to the greater community we can do it standing on the ground of science"The solution is to implement the best of biofeedback and neurofeedback and you can have a system that essentially acts as a surrogate guru, enabling you to measure changes in neuro-biology before, during, and after any number of different meditation practices.Objective Measurement data-brain activity (gamma, beta, alpha, theta, delta)-left/right brain hemishere coherence (see Dr Alarik Arenander EEG)-heart rate-heart rate variability (watch Dr Alan Watkins Coherence Showreel)-blood pressure-galvanic skin response-respiration rate-oxygen saturation (oximetrty)-temperature-ect (see mindmedia biofeedback)Then you simply pool all that data and create a mosaic of information, wherein numerous informative and practical correlations and patterns can be made, such as seeing what meditative practices are most effective for shifting neurophysiological patterns towards optimal.

processed_text: Referring to the first question I'd say that most of the narrower excess returns among money managers can be explained by index hugging. A lot of instituational investors hold either the index or a portfolio close to the index, for example 100 stocks out of the S&P500 with no stock making up more than 3% of assets. In such a world you would expect small SD of excess returns. That is a world where money managers manage their career risk first and dont want to be the best at delivering risk adjusted performance. Someone who truly cares about performance goes for a proven quant strategy like Joel Greenblatt, concentrated "deep value" like Seth Klarman, concentrated "compounding machines" like Warren Buffet, concentrated special situations (old school Joel Greenblatt), concentrated small cap stocks... or a mix of those.

author: @jimbeck6299
processed_text: He makes a great point that many parodists today are missing. They're so fast to jump on the knowing joke of a given song, like the rapey vibe of Blurred Lines. But that's too obvious. Instead, he ignores that and figures out what would best fit the beat, lyrics, etc. That's what separates typical parodists (which are also funny very often) from Weird Al. He is able to tap into the consciousness of modern society and focus on the most minute details instead of going for the quick laugh. Which puts him heads above the rest. In fact, this is a huge reason why even the best internet parodists besides Weird Al don't get huge releases.¬†

author: @renton9999
processed_text: Damien Boath Robert Headley actually, there are still some shows out there that still use cards for interviews, as they tend to be unscripted, and they prefer to have the host facing the guest rather than the cameras when asking the questions.¬† also, google tries not to use the more expensive equipment because it can get in the way of the audience's ability to enjoy the live show (in the room).¬† also, the space they used isn't a studio, but instead is a multipurpose space.one final thing, they commonly use interns rather than professional crews because interns are not part of unions, and the unions charge a fee on top of what the crew person would ask for.¬† then you have to add on the cost of the equipment which renting the high end stuff can get pricey.¬† It appears google is using consumer grade equipment that fits their needs, so it isn't very high tech but still does the job.¬† think of "Talks at Google" as a public access show.

author: @minty_Joe
processed_text: 1.) Lapel/lavalier mics were so 1970s-1990s.¬† They're inefficient for today's sound standards.¬† Start using headset mics.¬†2.) Have a sound technician on staff at the event to make it loud and clear.¬†3.) Don't skimp on having equalizers/notch filters in-line in-between the mixer and house amps, so they can control acoustic feedback.¬†4.) Add a compressor/limiter in-line in-between the mixer and recording device; this will guarantee that your recordings won't clip all the time.

processed_text: I have to defend electro shock therapy, not what ever bullshit they did to this guy, but the actual therapy. It really can treat some diseases.

author: @panpiper
processed_text: Electro shock therapy works by literally burning out through electrical overload, those synaptic connections that have the least resistance to the current due to being the most active in the brain. Sadly this burnout also accrues to memories and such, which is what leads to the memory loss often reported. Due to the brain being a fairly holographic system where memories are not necessarily stored in a single synaptic set, such memories can if they are strong enough, be recovered, to a degree. The disorientation and confusion that results is due to much the same effect, at least till the brain can rebuild cognitive synaptic networks to replace those that have been burned out.Defenders of the treatment assert that it is not brain damage because there is no 'gross structural' damage. Of course there isn't, it is synaptic, but it most emphatically IS damage. It is indeed possible that damaging the synaptic networks that are causing the psychiatric condition is worth the damage to the rest of the brain. It is a judgement call.¬†

author: @thrillho-v7v
processed_text: Yeah, the real deal is now generally called electroconvulsive therapy (ECT) to distinguish it from the terrible uses it was put to in the past. ECT can treat problems (such as some of the most severe cases of depression) better than anything else, though it does have serious side effects. Modern ECT is not like it was (ab)used in the past--the horror stories like One Flew Over the Cuckoo's Nest.It also has ABSOLUTELY NO PLACE in quackery like "conversion therapy".

author: @panpiper
processed_text: In short, life has whatever meaning you give it, and that includes meaning in one's work.I find it to be helpful to realize that in the free market (government and government collusive business is frequently a different story) any exchange of service for dollars (or other barter) is voluntary. Each side of the trade values what the other is giving more than they value what they are giving, else no trade would be made. In such a free exchange, both parties gain more value than they otherwise would have without the trade. The same goes for when someone is trading their service (employment) for wages. Any such free market work is contributing value to the world in direct proportion to how much people pay for the service. Someone who bakes bread for a living is feeding people. Someone who washes dishes is keeping people healthy. All free market work is inherently noble, in that it is contributing a real value to the world.

Toyota had (key word) a firm grip on this while its originators nurtured and shaped the Toyota Way, on the back of WW2, when people finally felt hope and excitement in rebuilding the world (awesome cars, guitars and aeroplanes etc). And somehow Google have managed to incite the same, albeit with internal, humanistic development rather than 'stuff', and also without starting a war. Very interesting talk. Will listen to this one a few more times!

author: @whartanto2
processed_text: I am highly skeptical. It sounds like another magic pill / silver bullet / snake oil solution to human performance. I bought the book but I couldn't bring myself to read past the first chapters - mostly because extreme sports do not interest me.At the moment, in absence of more consensus in the medical research community; I would chalk the probability of this being another fad as reasonably high.Ngati is right in saying that there is no need to believe. But statistically speaking, the number of radical ideas that turned out to be correct is not that high.

author: @ngatileprechaun
processed_text: whartanto2It sounds like another magic pill / silver bullet / snake oil solution to human performanceThe thing is that there's nothing really radical or magical about it. Buddhists, yogi's, meditators and explorers of consciousness, have been describing altered states of consciousness (and their means of attainment) for millenia. All we're doing now is testing to see if what they say has any substance. And surprising, it turns out that it does.¬† The great thing about modern science (esp. in the last 20 or so years) is that we can test any sort of claim about improving human performance by looking at the correlates of high performance and noting the actual physiological and neurological indications that are directly correlated to high performance. From there, it's just a matter of learning what triggers or causal variables there are to bring about those higher states of performance (or "flow states") with greater consistency. That's what science does. That's what guys like Csikszentmihalyi, Dr Alan Watkins, Dr Steven Peters, Kotler and Wheal et al are doing. On the other hand, I don't see any clear justification for skepticism or doubt, since everything these researchers are talking about are essentially based on legit scientific observations and repeatability that one can verify for themselves with a little homework.

author: @intralaminarnuclei8437
processed_text: whartanto2"I am highly skeptical. It sounds like"So am I. But I eventually realized that my skepticism wasn't really based on anything substantial, other than the fact that "it sounds like ", which is really to say that I wasn't actually applying any rationality in assessing claims regarding flow or higher human performance, but was relying more on emotionality (Since when did "sounds like xyz to me" ever qualify as a rational or scientific means of assessment? .. the short answer is, it doesn't.)"I bought the book but I couldn't bring myself to read past the first chapters - mostly because extreme sports do not interest me."Extreme sports don't particularly interest me either. But it didn't matter, because my interest concerns understanding high performance and human potential. So it made logical sense to read about the research into extreme sports and what the researchers and scientists discovered that relates to increasing human performance."At the moment, in absence of more consensus in the medical research community; I would chalk the probability of this being another fad as reasonably high."If there's one thing that's consistent in the history of science, it's that consensus is always behind the times. But personally, having read extensively on the subject of human performance and talked to people in medicine, education, sports psychology, etc, I can say, without a doubt, that the consensus is changing, and that a lot more educated people are realizing that there's more room for evolution / growth / development / enhancement / and performance in humans than we previously thought possible."Ngati is right in saying that there is no need to believe. But statistically speaking, the number of radical ideas that turned out to be correct is not that high."Dude, look around you. You think you're living in a non-radical world? Do you think what science has created over the last 200 years is not radical? We live in radicality. Therefore, statistically speaking, the number of radical ideas that turned out to be correct is extremely high. Think about it.

author: @whartanto2
processed_text: Intralaminar Nuclei1, Skepticism should be the default attitude. Just as in the court it is innocent until proven guilty; it is scepticism until proven by sufficient evidence.2.¬†The consensus is always behind the times because they are awaiting for sufficient evidence before making up their minds. Medicine's success comparatively speaking, is because they stop following theory driven path and start following empirical data. It is not perfect. But it is the more successful path.3. That is the false logic. This world has seen a great advance in medical science, thus it is radical world. If we believe that there is one objective truth, thus it is clear that multiple explanation to one event can only lead to larger number of false explanation than correct one.The path of science is full of radical ideas that have been disproven; it just does not get mentioned by anyone anymore. Lamarckism inheritance in genes for example.¬†Phrenology approach to neuroscience, as another.When a radical idea turned to be true, the very weight of evidence will shift the consensus. Neuroplasticity is a great example of this. Yes, waiting for the evidence to decide is slow. But for every truth, there are¬†unlimited number¬†of possible theory that human imagination can conjure up.¬†

So it was pretty disappointing to not hear about anything really new, as maybe my memory is off but I remember the first talk not only singing the praises of what you could do now but the exciting future ahead. Being able to 3D print anything. News stories have kept coming out showing how now you can print metal, circuit boards are possible, printing food is a thing but this talk really felt like that exciting future has now settled into a small business that's struggling to break out of that dot matrix era, where all the innovation seems to be happening around making the dot matrix printer faster, better looking and better at representing one font rather than moving us onto photo printers which is where the masses really started to get into printing, turning it from a specialist thing to something almost everyone had in their home.That's not to say I didn't enjoy the talk or that I don't love what makerbot are doing. I do! I'm re-calibrating my expectations to something more realistic :)

processed_text: Nas¬†Best &¬†My #1¬†Fav Mc of all Time..My top 5 DOA no order :Chuck D/ Common, Biggie, KRS, Rakim & Nas

I really think that Nas is not only a great artist, but also a special person. I live in Austria and here Hip Hop is not actually a genre that is represented much and I don't notice a lot of things that go on in the Hip Hop world in America, since I'm too far away and the information doesn't spread on to me. So, watching this interview, watching this man talk about his life, his record, the people he worked with, and so on, this actually gave me an amazing view into the life and way of a big artist, as Nas is, and shows me how he isn't that different from anyone of us writing lyrics, writing poetry, living what is meant to be in an 'artful' way.I, too, write myself and I just find it so inspirational to hear about all the stuff he has to say, and you can tell there is a lot on his mind, and all you're catching on the radio over here is trashy commercial music, that doesn't have that depth and sense that Hip Hip actually means to represent. Finally, what I want to point out to is that it's sad that at some places, like my home Austria, you just can't get in touch with people like Nas, who with their words can change the way of thinking of a person and can bring sympathy and understanding of some kind, and that's why to me Hip Hop is a feeling that certainly goes all around the world, but, however, still 'lives' in the United States, where you have the actual access to that culture and way of living and their representatives.

author: @NickKolirousis
processed_text: In the last 10 minutes, Mr. Jerry Harvey speaks on something that is going to develop while my company is working around this the last 3 years now, and i can't wait to have some competition on this.. xaxa.Well in my opinion, the hardest work isn't in any of all of theses features in this IEM but i have to say that is very impressive though. The big problem is to have a portable system with REALTIME DSP capabilities, with a touchscreen interface in as small form factor case that is powered up my 2 or 4 small batteries something like the receiver beltpack of these days.. Having that in mind the whole idea is getting even worse if you think and try to answer this question.."How about to control my IEM from an app using my iOS or Android smartphone?"... This is where i (my company) have been working into this the last 1 one year now, and this is the one of some most difficult situations to resolve, cause having the issue of Real-time monitoring, none of the above (iOS or Android) smartphones hardware or software is capable right now to run real-time DSP eq,dyn-comp,multiband comp,limiter etc.. without any Latency issues. SHARK or SigmaStudio processors may be the answer...or not?maybe Mr Harvey is already know? ho knows.... ;) ...Nice video and speaking.! :D

author: @SianaGearz
processed_text: OK, i really don't think common hardware platforms, be they Android or iOS based, are too slow for 10band eq + a dynamic processor. Or what DSP you need? In fact i think i could implement EQ+dynamics even on the built in DSP of the old Soundblaster Live, and that's a piece of crap compared to any modern processor, whether DSP or application-oriented.Latency has two sources. One source is the interface. On iOS, you can get low latency-ish (well urgh) audio, on Android you can not, but neither is a hardware issue. I think you can start off a hardware of Android device if you can get QNX for it, or just stay with Android and work around large parts of the Android system and have your own pathway from audio in the kernel to the processing software. You'll do away with most of this kind of latency at some point.Other source is the algorithmic latency. IIRs are gonna do just fine, and in EQ use e.g. are very little computational impact too. You really need to get this right.I think you should segment the problem space better. You want a device which speaks Bluetooth so you can control it from a handset - perhaps forget about it having its own controls and a display at first. Get a PC running Linux stand in for your DSP, get it to process audio by your algorithm, work on your algorithms, work on your mobile apps. Disregard the interface latency and care only about algorithmic latency. Then judge the performance of your algorithm (do use whatever old or weak hardware you can find for that), and chose the bare-metal hardware platform accordingly which you can control over SPI or whatever. You'll then just need a random bluetooth microcontroller with SPI and you're set. I think you want to aim to release your product fast and solve one problem instead of taking years and doing everything you can think of - you can leave that for later.AD Shark/Sigma for DSP? Maybe, but remember the classics. The Moto X still has a TMS320 in it, but these days MSP430 is also curious.

processed_text: 1. Network infrastructure (on which 99.999% of Rifkin's additional zero marginal cost economy rests and relies on) is NOT zero marginal cost. In fact, nowhere there. Neither are computing devices like computer, phablets, smartphones, google glasses, Internet of things, etc.2. New, original (non-100%-bit-to-bit copied) content is NOT zero marginal cost.3. Food is not marginal cost. Neither is housing. 3D printer raw materials, 3D printers, electricity to run all the cloud computing data centers, etc. Or any of the other externalities NOT included in Rifkin's model of building additional units of zero marginal cost products/services.4. Rifkin appears not to see what is the huge, direct-risk-to-life of having microwave radio emissions embedded everywhere. That's a HUGE, non-zero externality cost, which in the end will be internalized into Total Cost of Usership in the end. He could start by reading EMF risk research data by Persson.So, the question is: what remains in the Rifkin's zero marginal cost?Even excess thought (which consumes calories) is bound by non-zero marginal cost limitations.If you start thinking about it, it's quite clearly that Rifkin does not understand physics or reality, but is playing with pure ideas which cannot be implemented in a system which is bound by 2nd law of thermodynamics.

author: @dvmovie
processed_text: bighands69 This is "the only system that is viable today that enables trade and innovation..."Well... this may have been the case in the past.¬† But with our advancements in technology over the past few decades, it is simply no longer true.¬† Especially with innovation.¬† There are many recent studies which have shown that our monetary system, based on competition and financial-incentive, is actually detrimental to innovation and progress.¬† However, when people are put into situations where they can collaborate rather than compete, the result is an increase in creativity and performance.Corporations hoard scientific knowledge for the sake of advantage.¬† And researchers are often made to work on projects where profits take precedence over true scientific intent, another example of how our monetary system impedes progress. ¬†If we could only take advantage of our current communication technology, and work in collaboration with EVERYONE who has something to contribute, imagine the speed at which scientific breakthroughs and innovation might occur... free from the restrictions of the monetary system.And trade?¬† The emerging reality of "zero-marginal cost", our ability to make more with less, automated production systems, 3-D printing, etc... these might transform the act of "trade", as we've known it, into something we might call "localized production and distribution".And anyway, trade is just another corrupt mechanism of the money game, where Governments and Corporations collude to rig the game for the benefit of a few.¬† They can manipulate scarcity in order to maximize profits.¬† And they do.¬† They'll take food from poor countries where it's grown (and where people are starving), and ship it to where people have the most money to buy it. ¬†In fact, starvation, human suffering, environmental degradation... these consequences are never even taken into account in our monetary economy.¬† They're just an unfortunate result, a "negative externality", inherent to the system.. along with growing inequality, escalating conflicts, the destruction of our ecosystems, and all the rest.Sorry to ramble.¬† But these issues are important.¬† Crucial.¬† Potentially catastrophic.¬† I mean, does anyone really believe -- in a monetary economy built around endless growth and consumption -- that we can pass along a healthy, sustainable planet to our future generations?¬† I don't think there's any way that's possible.¬† Which leaves us no choice...

author: @jazzimpact
processed_text: I find Rifkin's work immensely stimulating and important.¬†I think his ideas become even more useful when tempered by rational skepticism.I found this commentary disturbing but also important to consider- especially for those who are not fortunate enough to be working in one of the fledgling co-operations of the collaborative commons such as Google.The push-backDavid Appelbaum ‚Ä¢ 9 days agoI believe Mr. Rifkin is absurdly over optimistic! The amount of political will to implement the level of infrastructure improvements required is not remotely feasible in our polarized political climate. Plus the notion of the Social Commons assumes a highly educated and entrepreneurial population. Given the appalling state of our educational system how are the majority of our people going to achieve the level of self sufficiency required to participate effectively? Moreover under a social commons system the means for truly complex goods and services and the associated wages concentrates wealth and power even further at the top leaving a culture of barter serfs gleaning the digital fields of the mega corporations. Mr. Rifkin's ideas are dangerous in the extreme and do absolutely nothing to correct the extreme social imbalance and dislocation we're seeing now. Whenever prophets speak of the shining city on the hill they never talk about how the plumbing works. We need real practical solutions for bringing dignity, self sufficiency, and security for the majority of our people. Mr. Rifkin does not advance that with his glorious digital future.

This is all guesswork, what I've noticed about Google is that it goes after billion dollar ideas now, small stuff like say, Google Reader, pah, get rid of that. They also take much longer term views on business ideas than any other company I know of. Take the whole Google Maps and Google Earth and everything that entails, street view and so on. They started throwing huge amounts of money on that, buying up companies like Keyhole to somewhat accelerate there way into it but clearly at the time, there just was no business you could run on what they were doing. A huge multi billion dollar business. The list goes on but I won't over elaborate for the sake of it, we all know about Googles self driving cars, plans to map the globe with hot air balloons that can carry internet to all. All of these huge business ideas all seem to have around a 10 year spin up time. So that's what interests me about them buying heavily into aging today. author: @KalilAWilson
processed_text: "Coming back to the internet, what‚Äôs interesting is what is available. and what isn‚Äôt readily available because people don‚Äôt see it.Like you won‚Äôt find a word about anything I‚Äôve said in the press or in commentary or in discussion, although it‚Äôs all extremely timely. Very timely. Not arcane scholarship.But it‚Äôs right in front of our eyes, but not there.And when you come back to the power of the internet, I think it comes back to us: we don‚Äôt use it.We don‚Äôt use the resource for the purposes for which it could be used - to break through the silence, oppression. domination, terror, violence - and bring the reality of the world to people.So the internet, potentially, is a wonderful tool, but only if you decide to use it.If you decide to leave it in the hands of private power, of power systems whether state or private, sure it‚Äôll be used as a way to oppress, undermine, and dominate.But that‚Äôs a choice. You don‚Äôt have to."

author: @KalilAWilson
processed_text: "There are a number of dogmas about language, which I think are being systematically refuted - they are held by linguists too, I should say, not just in the general public - which are probably false, and which I think are being undermined by current research.The introductory comments said that I‚Äôm supposed to be a contrarian, so I‚Äôll try to keep to that. This is a minority view.For example, one general assumption about language - the philosophy of language, common understanding the linguistics of psychology - is that language is primarily a means of communication, and that it evolved as a means of communication.Probably that‚Äôs totally false. It seems that language evolved and is designed as a mode of creating and interpreting thought, basically.I can be used to communicate. Everything people do can be used to communicate. You communicate by your hairstyle, style of walk, everything, and yes, language can be used to communicate, but it doesn‚Äôt seem to be part of it‚Äôs design.It‚Äôs design seems to be radically different, and even seems to undermine communication.If you look carefully at the structure of language you find case after case, right at the core of language design, where there are conflicts between what would be efficient for communication, and what is efficient for the specific biological design of language.And in every case that‚Äôs known, communicative efficiency is sacrificed. It just isn‚Äôt a consideration.I think that‚Äôs a conclusion that has very wide spread significance.In order to establish it, you have to look at very technical work. It‚Äôs not the kind of thing you can explain in two minutes of exposition, but its not profound, it‚Äôs not quantum physics. A half an hour would certainly suffice, and I think it‚Äôs of pretty far-reaching consequence.Another general belief about language, again, almost a dogma in all the relevant fields ‚Äî philosophy, linguistics and so on - is that the minimal meaningful elements in language, the sort of word-like things, pick out entities in the extra mental world, like a river, something a physicist could identify.That turns out to be true for animal systems, animal communication systems, the symbols that appear the actions that are carried out do apparently have a one to one correlation with mind-independent events. So some particular call of a monkey will be related to leaves fluttering, predators coming, or in a hummingbird, some hormonal change.It‚Äôs just not true of language. Linguistic elements do not have that property.Actually, this was understood by Aristotle. It was understood in the 17th and 18th centuries, interesting work on it.The entities that we construct in our communiques, discourse, expression, interpretation are largely mental -partially mental objects.There are ways in which they are modes in which we interpret phenomena, but they don‚Äôt pick out entities in the world, that a natural scientist could identify without looking into our minds.That tells us a lot about the nature of language, and about our own nature.Language is the core human property, and this was understood by Darwin, and by a long tradition before him.And it‚Äôs very different from the way it is usually conceived.I think those are among the conclusions that have pretty wise spread significance Again let me stress again, a very minority view, very few linguists would agree with this.But I think over time I suspect it will become clear."

author: @duckmanjoel
processed_text: Could you create a 'virtual Neanderthal clone'? In other words, could a computer program be created that understands genes and how those genes are expressed against certain environments (anything from a hunter gather environment to modern day industrial environments). For the 'virtual Neanderthal', you put in what we know about the human genome and the hunter gatherer environment with all the dangers and risks, and then you make changes to the genome to see how that organism responds. Is the gene advantages or neutral or beneficial? Seems like such a program, once established, would be invaluable as genes are discovered. And to keep it completely modern, for example, the program should be able to recognize the change to the genome, for example PKU; but when phenylalanine is taken out of the environment, the individual thrives. The program should, of course, be able to suggest, if not identify, what in the environment is causing the distress to the 'virtual individual'. Such a program would be a bigger endeavor than the sequencing of the human genome, but certainly would be worth the expense once established. I hope to meet Dr. Paabo one day. I admire how he admitted he was wrong when he said that we would never sequence the genome of the Neanderthal. So maybe we will see a Neanderthal clone in 'the virtual reality.'¬†

author: @Dreamydre15
processed_text: Their was no team of doctors. She took hormone blockers before she hit puberty followed by estrogen (female hormones) so she never went through male puberty just female secondary puberty which allowed her to basically develop into a woman - wide hips, breasts, voice and all those characteristics came naturally. Starting hormones before puberty is probably the best opportunity if you're going to transition, sadly most places it's not allowed until you're 18 and passed puberty. By then you'll have already gotten a deep voice, etc that some (but not all) trans women do. Also she was never born male. Gender is defined by what you identify as - sex is what you are born. Her sex was male, as a baby she couldn't of course identify herself and so she was assigned (gender) male at birth, but she mentally was assigned as female. That's where gender dysphoria comes in which is an actual medical condition. It's all really not that complex, once you're more educated on a topic the more you understand. (:

author: @ConstantinVlad
processed_text: The most spectacular failure of AdB's talk was his omission of ‚Äùold school news‚Äù - which in very few instances is still surviving even today. A respectable ‚Äùold school‚Äù print media outlet - such as The New York Times - would provide virtually everything he complains it lacks: the basic information, all sorts of context, op-eds presenting multifaceted analysis, editorials/opinions, photojournalism (where applicable). Even special editions.This is still doable - and done - in both print and online (UK's The Guardian also produces some terrific pieces of journalism).The main culprit for the current status of ‚ÄùThe News‚Äù ain't ‚ÄùThe News‚Äù, for once - it's the public. Who rushed towards a ‚Äùfast news‚Äù menu, with all of its shortcomings. All that most of ‚ÄùThe News‚Äù has done was to respond to the demand of its audience, oftentimes at its own peril. But constantly refusing to update its economic model was a fatal move.The vast majority of good journalists, those who think with their heads and don't bow to their bosses, have left the industry for good. They were replaced by drones subservient to their employers. The funny thing is that these drones are better suited to cater the needs of large swathes of the ‚Äùnew public‚Äù, which has the attention span of a fruit fly.I'm not saying we should go backwards and his isn't a rant; I found the presentation to be most entertaining. And wrong on oh-so-many other levels I won't get into. :)

author: @nthperson
processed_text: Our history is a history dominated by two processes: (1) conflicts of territorial conquest between those who think of themselves as sovereign people, with no obligation to respect the equal birthright of others to a place on this planet; and (2) the internal development of hierarchies within societies that inevitably have established entrenched landed privilege as a basis for law and societal norms.Along the way the idea that the planet is a commons to be equitably shared has essentially disappeared as a core moral principle. The majority of people passively accept the idea of private property in nature, with only a nominal expression of concern over monopolization of natural resources or the evils of land speculation.Social democracy has done nothing to overcome the destructive influence on human behavior of pervasive landlessness. This is not to suggest that most of us today should be living on a family farm, growing our own food and relying on self-sufficiency as Thomas Jefferson believed was the only basis for the survival of a democratic republic. Few of us own more land than that which exists under our primary residence. Fully one-third of households in the United States own no land at all, thus it is no surprise that households that live in rental housing have a much lower net worth than the two-thirds who at least own a residential property.Roughly one-half of the land area of the United States is in private hands. In terms of land area, just a handful of corporations and wealthy individuals own vast acreages of land. Two individuals each own land equal in size to the state of Delaware. But, that is not the most important measure of land monopoly in the United States. Most destructive is the concentrated holding of land value, of land in the central business districts of our major cities and suburban communities. The handful of economists who have focused on this issue as a major cause of poverty estimate (estimate because there are no accurate statistics collected or published), that 95 percent of the nation's land value is controlled by around 3 percent of the population, as well as foreign nationals and foreign corporate interests.The impact on our society is enormous. Land monopoly means that a major portion of the wealth produced is transferred from producers to non-producers (i.e.., to a rentier elite, who as a land owner produce nothing and provide no serivces in return). The easiest example to understand is the absentee land owner who leases land to the highest bidder for whatever purpose, collects the ground rent, and takes no risk as a producer or goods and services.Crime will only get worse as the power of the rentier elite expands, leaving less and less for others. What is needed is public policy changes that will address this problem, creating more opportunity for people to rise out of poverty and begin to realize the promise of social democracy. The most important change we can adopt is a change in how government raises its revenue, moving to land's rental value as THE main source of public revenue so that land is no longer hoarded or held for speculative gain.

author: @icRegions
processed_text: This underlies the importance of government of the people, by the people, for the people - all the people of a given jurisdiction - nation, state, province, county, municipality. Security is the primary purpose of community - the fundamental community motive. The tendency of humans to seek power and dominate needs to be managed by the spiritual mores of humanity. Any human organization can become a predator, rather than a protector. "Greater Community Spirituality" and other books by Marshall Vian Summers puts these challenges into a language that enables the hard earned wisdom of our social evolution to thoughtfully be put to use.¬†

author: @williambeeman2905
processed_text: I recommend the book and this video, but the techniques are at least a hundred years old. Madsbjerg and Rasmussen are trying to alert the business world to the techniques of cultural anthropology applied to business--ethnographic research that reveals the assumptions of preferences and action of which people are themselves unaware because they are so commonplace to the people themselves. Business Anthropology is becoming essential for the business world, and Madsbjerg and Rasmussen are showing precisely why no company can be without this perspective.

author: @MoerreNoseshine
processed_text: @12:30 and on - don't blame others, blame yourself: Oversimplification. Sure it would be nice and it IS a real phenomenon, that always blaming others thing. However, his advice works for ANYONE but not for EVERYONE (like most of those money-related motivational pieces of advice). Meaning, anyone who follows the advice can have success, so that part is true.But what happens if everyone does it? Then much of that kind of advice falls flat. In this context, there is only so much any given market can take, restaurants, bars etc (or anything else). So when you have only motivated intelligent people who never blame others and try their hardest, you STILL have about the same failure rate.So that kind of advice DOES work - in small doses. Don't try to put any such "motivators" in charge of a country or the world. My comment is specifically about that section around 12,13 minutes ONLY, I didn't watch the rest (not interested, not because I think it's a bad interview; I was only mildly interested in the subject to begin with).

author: @dantro78
processed_text: Michael Hasenstein,I agree that motivational speaking often preaches an oversimplified view of the world and the process through which one can better themselves.¬† However, you have to remember that when a motivator steps into a room and speaks to a crowd, if they can reach just one person, they've succeeded.I've worked as a performing musician and music teacher for a number of years.¬† In that time, I've done many seminars and clinics about improving as a musician, largely centered on practice techniques.¬† How many of these young musicians will actually follow my advice and apply the work ethic and approaches I've shown them?¬† Almost none of them.¬† Why?¬† Because that's just the way it is, and I've learned to accept that as such.¬† One can be the most entertaining and effective communicator, but it ultimately is incumbent on the individual to take the advice and apply the work ethic presented.My point is: If only one person in a crowded room hears what Jon Taffer says and they decide to alter their efforts as a result, than the seminar was an overwhelming success.

author: @StudSupreme
processed_text: Joe Young¬†That's not correct. Dress goes beyond peer groups or social sets. Manner of dress also communicates visually with shapes and color combinations. In the same way that a bull reacts to a red cloth waved in front of it, humans react to colors, intensities, combinations of colors, patterns, contrasts and shapes. This is what is so surprising about Temple Grandin's wardrobe choices. She has made a great effort to understand people and interact with them successfully at a high level of professionalism. However, her wardrobe not only contrasts with that, but acts against it.

author: @MrJoeYoung
processed_text: You claim that what I said is 'not correct', but it is, you just expanded it on it further. Colour and its effects on people is something I know a fair amount about as I use applications of it in my daily life, so I'm fully aware that humans react to colours, patterns, contrasts and shapes. However for the vast majority it's not in the same way that a Bull reacts to red as Bulls have dichromatic vision and are therefore colour blind. They don't react to red at all as it looks more green to them, instead they react to the movement of the cloth.Temple's wardrobe choice is hers to make, and some of us react very differently to fabrics, colours, textures and visual information than others. The one huge point that you appear to be overlooking is that Temple is not neurotypical and so the rules you think apply across the board don't apply to her.She is far more than the sum of her parts, and considerably more than any uniform you wish her to wear. Her very presence on that stage and the esteem with which she is held tells us just how important a dress code is. I applaud her individuality and am glad that she can defy convention and still command respect.I really don't see why what she is wearing matters so much to you.

Think about this: for decades our government has paid for studies but yet we still have massive chemicals in our food, our clothes, personal care products, our home (cleaning supplies, paper products, furniture, carpet, paint etc), baby products (OMG) and poor product labeling. So where did all money go to support these studies? As we continue to get more sick and our children born into our world, have toxic chemicals at birth, then compounded by our air, food, clothes and let's not forget the drug industry. Where is the outrage?

processed_text: Tom Adamson¬†Tom, Richard Dawkins talks about exactly the same thing as the child arranging an alphabet but in a different analogy, he says if a monkey bashes on a keyboard, what are the chances he might get a quote by Shakespeare right? He does the math, and the odds is an extremely large number, making natural selection impossible if that were the case, so how does it work?He describes natural selection as a faulty lock code where you are rewarded for guessing at least 1 number right. Suppose you have a lock code that consists of 3 numbers. Chances you might get it right is 1 out of 1000 tries. Whereas if you hear a tick every time you get a number right, chances you might get the right number would be 1 out of 30 tries, because you only have to try 10 numbers (9 numbers including the zero) on each code, multiply the same number by 3 to get the number of tries you need for 3 codes.¬†The same goes to the monkey bashing on a keyboard, if the computer only selects the letters the monkey types if it is right, then it will end up typing the right code. Though a computer is intelligent, and it knows what the answer is, natural selection is 'blind' to the future, hence his book's name: The Blind Watchmaker. He even has a documentary by the same name, just look it up on Youtube and you'll find it. Watch that documentary if you want to understand how natural selection can still create complex beings even though it's 'blind'. He explains it very clearly.¬†

author: @zak8953
processed_text: I'm very respectful of Andrew Scheps for his experience and commitment to promoting lossless audio formats, and also promoting better quality audio (we need better quality audio!). I'm a bit worried about where he's getting his information from, because @ 16-bit 44.1kHz (for playback) all of the information for perfectly recreating an an analog sound wave is already contained in the¬†digital file. Anything else is unnecessary. Check out xiph.org. The (I believe if I'm not mistaken) founder of xiph.org Monty is VERY knowledgeable about audio (analog and digital) and in this article (http://people.xiph.org/~xiphmont/demo/neil-young.html) he explains in great detail why 24-bit 96kHz is very silly, and how 192kHz can actually distort audio. The gist is that for playback 16-bit 48kHz is most likely the maximum bit depth and sample rate you would even want to use for perfect analog sound wave recreation, and after that it's just useless. The reason that it is extended to 48kHz is for the DAC filter fall off I believe. That part is a little bit over my head. I'm not sure how Mr. Scheps can sit there and tell people that vinyl is superior to a digital format, and suggest that 24-bit 96kHz audio is superior to 16-bit 48kHz audio when science is clearly not supporting this. If you want further information also check out the neat video that Monty proving that 16-bit 44.1kHz contains all the information needed to recreate an analog sound wave. He even uses analog oscilloscope and and analog wave generator, then directly compares them to the digital counterpart. It's extremely informative. No disrespect to Mr. Scheps, but he should look further into the science of sound.

author: @MikaelJohnston
processed_text: The resolution is higher across the entire bandwidth for one thing but there are many other reasons why some people believe audio at higher sample rates can sound better. With that said and science aside (I've read compelling arguments on both sides) I can hear the difference in my studio and that's all that really matters to me. I don't have an ax to grind one way or the other, if it didn't sound better I'd be happy to do everything at 16 bit 44.1 KHZ, it would certainly save a ton of space and processing power. I recommend before getting too caught up in technical papers to do some critical listening in a proper recording studio and hear for yourself if you haven't already.

author: @zak8953
processed_text: I've got an HDSPe AIO and it's capable of all of all of the "common" sample rates (and everything in between, because you can adjust the DDP per sample). I've actually tested 24-bit 44.1 kHz vs. 16 recently with tools and there is a difference. This is probably due to quantization artifacts when truncating to 16-bits from 24. I'm doing some tests with oscilloscopes using iZotope's MBIT+ dither algorithm (oscilloscopes can "hear" better than we'll ever be able to). I need to investigate more. 192 kHz does sound different, but according to oscilloscope this is because it's imparting some sort of distortion. Maybe that's incorrect. But at first glance that looks like what's going on. I'm also not bashing higher sample rates for recording/processing because I've learned recently there are some advantages, like emulating analog synths (i.e. NI's MONARK). But truthfully, if you're hearing more accurate audio when comparing 24-bit 44.1 kHz to for example 24-bit 96 kHz for PLAYBACK. You'd be the first. As far as I understand NO ONE has ever successfully demonstrated this in a research setting. Please, (sincerely) let me know if I'm mistaken or wrong. The various scientific articles I've read state that (for playback) 44.1 kHz is even above what we already need. That with what some would argue is already overkill resolution 24-bit depth (but it doesn't add any type of distortion or problems so it's just fine to use in conjunction with any audio sampling rate) is all we'll ever need (for playback). I think that's good news! When I'm done with my projects I'll be exporting @ 44.1 kHz 24-bit depth. Because that's what the experts who build the tools are telling me I should do.Seriously, watch this video:http://www.xiph.org/video/vid2.shtmlI'm totally not trying to diminish the art of mixing/producing (it's what I love the most!) but when it comes down to the technical details, I'm going to trust the electronics engineers, programmers, mathematicians, and psychoacoustic scientific researchers over a dude that USES the tools those experts build. Wouldn't you?
