author: @splinterchaos1
processed_text: Actually, he was giving a very rough version of Anselm's Ontological Argument, which states that when one conceives of a greatest conceivable being, one must necessarily conceive that it exists. Purely because if one were to conceive of a greatest conceivable being that does NOT exist, then it would not be the greatest conceivable being. To Anselm, the greatest conceivable being must exist.It's compelling, but problematic. The first problem is that saying that existence necessarily makes something better requires more argument than Anselm gives. A second argument, (which is weaker, but builds on the first problem), is that I can conceive of the Greatest Conceivable Cookie that exists, but that does not mean that the Greatest Conceivable Cookie actually exists.Still, it is badass that he just burst out with metaphysical arguments for fun.

author: @sorsocksfake
processed_text: splinterchaos1Definitely badass. Personally my problem with the argument is that it ends up conceiving a real god: its reality is still only imagined. "I imagine a real god" is the same as "I imagine a god".¬†If one tries to say the imagination is better because it actually reflects an existing entity, I want to know how that follows: I would think the reflected entity's existence isn't a quality of the imagined being.¬†Likewise one can call out that god is too great for our imagination, at which point the intended point fails at the start: one cannot actually conceive such a being, so whatever Anselm imagined, wasn't god.¬†

author: @feydrautha012
processed_text: sorsocksfakeColbert likes to seek out the most absurd positions that people take and emulate those positions. There are few "arguments" for god(s) that are more absurd that the ontological argument (unless perhaps you only take it as far as to conclude that it is possible for "powerful" being(s) to exist, however subjective "powerful" may be, but this actually makes no movement towards proving deism or theism). So it makes perfect sense for Colbert to embrace that argument. The only problem is that he has to explain it as very few get the reference.

processed_text: *****When someone publicly insults me based on faulty premises, I feel it's necessary to correct them publicly so that they and others can recognize the mistake. I also feel that when someone mistakenly insults someone else, that person should expect to be corrected, and that this is beneficial to them because it helps them to learn from their mistakes.Why don't I remove the comment? I agree that 720p is available right now. However, for the above stated reasons, I wish to refute your statements. Because leaving the unedited comment in place provides an unimpeachable record of exactly what I said in my first post, I have what I need to prove that your premises are incorrect. After I'm finished proving conclusively that you are wrong, I'm willing to edit the comment to point out that the situation has been rectified.Why didn't I remove the comment before you saw it? Because until you responded, I wasn't aware that they'd made higher resolutions available. YouTube never notified me and I didn't happen to come back to this, so I had no way of knowing; you are therefore blaming me for responding to something in state A as though it was in state B. It is in state B now, but at the time of the post in question, it was in state A. I cannot be expected to act on knowledge of an event that hasn't taken place yet, and which I have no specific reason to believe will happen.Here are the premises of your first post:It was available in HD when I accused you of idiocy, about one week ago.Therefore, in saying that it wasn't available in HD several months ago, you are an idiot.In order for that to be correct, you'd need to prove the following premises:P1: If it was available in HD about a week ago, it was also available in HD a few months ago.P2: It was available in HD about a week ago.P3: You said it wasn't available in HD a few months ago.C1: I must be correct, and you must be incorrect.P4: If you're incorrect, you're an idiot.P5: You're incorrect.C2: You are incorrect and therefore an idiot.Regarding P1, you suppose, but don't actually know, that YouTube gave me an option to play the video in HD several months ago. Premises cannot be based on supposition. Therefore, P1 is invalid.P2 is true; it was indeed available in HD about a week ago. However, P1 is invalid; since P1 must be valid in order for P2 and P3 to be relevant, P2 is irrelevant.P3 is true; I did indeed say that it wasn't available in HD a few months ago. However, this is irrelevant for the same reason as P2 (P1 is invalid).C1 is invalid because the supporting premises are all invalid or irrelevant.P4 is debatable. Even a genius can make a mistake - indeed, it's often necessary to make decisions that may well be mistaken in the process of selecting the best way to do something; yet a genius is not an idiot by any reasonable definition. You yourself have made mistakes, such as the ones I've illustrated here. The very premise of an insult is that you're better than the other person concerning what the insult describes.¬†It would be hypocritical for you to insult someone for doing the same thing you yourself are doing and have done countless times.P5 is invalid because it assumes C1, which is also invalid.C2 is invalid because P4 is debatable and P5 is invalid.Your second post makes a statement that has already been addressed at the top of this post, and then it goes into some invalid logic.Here is your logic:I highly doubt it would take over 6 Months for the 720p to encode. I reiterate my "You Idiot" for you not being able to notice.Or, Too proud of your thumbs up maybe... FoolÔªøStated formally:P1: What I highly doubt is impossible.P2: You stated something that I highly doubt.C1: Your statement is impossible.P3: Your impossible statement is wrong.P4: If you're wrong, you're an idiot.C2: You're an idiot.P5: If you can't admit you're wrong because of votes, you're a fool.P6: You may be too proud of your votes to admit you're wrong.C3: You're a fool.P1 is invalid because impossible necessarily means a probability of 0, whereas highly doubt admits a probability of >0. In your own words, you don't believe it's impossible.P2 is correct, but as it relies on P1 to support C1 and P1 is invalid, it's irrelevant.C1 is unsupported by P1 and P2, and is therefore invalid.P3 relies on C1, which is invalid, making P3 invalid.P4 is invalid for the same reason that the first post's P4 is invalid (see above paragraph that begins with "P4 is debatable").C2 is unsupported by P3 and P4, and is therefore invalid.P5 is an opinion. I could agree with it, but it isn't necessarily true.P6 is invalid beacuse it's indeterminate. It can't be used to determine the truth of anything because it doesn't state whether or not I'm too proud.C3 is a concrete conclusion that depends on premises that are either opinions or indeterminate. You cannot arrive at "you are" by way of "you may be" because "you are" requires information that is not made available by "you may be".So far you're zero for two. Would you like to keep going? I sure would! Disassembling arguments and checking them for consistency is a lot of fun.

author: @christheghostwriter
processed_text: It is true. Record needles have more room/time to vibrate in the long, slow grooves at the beginning of a record than they do at the end, where that part of the record is spinning more quicklyImagine spinning a small object around you at the end of a long string (like a big metal washer or something). It will make a sound as it moves through the air. Now shorten the string significantly, and spin it again. The pitch of the sound will be higher, because the washer will be spinning around you more quickly and the sound vibrations it makes as it moves through the air will be smaller/shorter. It's the same concept with the record needle.Does that make sense?

author: @muzicaz
processed_text: the ghostwriter¬†Very interesting! Anyway, nothing is really perfect but I still prefere the vinyl sound...

author: @mvl71
processed_text: the ghostwriter¬†I could be wrong, of course, but it seems to me a vinyl record spins at a constant speed of 33 1/3 rpm. It doesn't get any faster near the end...At the start of the record the needle covers more of the groove per second than at the end, so more and more music has to fit in less and less inches of groove as it nears the end of the record. I imagine that music at the start of the groove is therefore recorded more detailed than near the end.

author: @garyteves4077
processed_text: The ukulele is a nylon-stringed instrument. As such, it does not stay in tune as long as, say, a folk guitar. If you play as vigorously as Jake can, you are going to want to check your tuning after each piece. If you carefully observe, he will play some quick notes while the audience is clapping. If it sounds off to his ear, he can then quickly check the tuner, tune up and be ready before anyone gets bored. So, it's more for the audience's benefit. As for having concert pitch in his head, even a beginner quickly learns the string intervals by the "my dog has fleas" method, so, no problem there.

processed_text: This sounds very much like a lot of Spanish Guitar playing that I have heard, yet it is done on a ukulele. It sounds both familiar to the ear and yet unknown, new and somehow aged. It is extraordinary and we wish him all the best. He is definitely a class act and is in a league all his own. Passion and hard work have married themselves together to produce this and I am privileged to have witnessed the result. Bravo, friend!

processed_text: Dr. Tuttle has brought out aspects that he has attributed to various sources, but essentially their original source emanates from Hindu philosophies. The core tenets of Patanjali Yoga Sutras - Yama & Niyama ( Social and Individual disciplines) which is the essential purification processes for meditation. Eventually, we are what we eat and what we think, and purification of the sources of these is the first part of the evolution of man. Vedic society got this in India. Unfortunately, it has been overrun by the middle-eastern philosophies and then the colonial take-over has let to the mother civilization and culture being painted wrongly.The Hindu system codified the vegetarian system along with sustainable agriculture. Dr. Tuttle perhaps does not get this at all when he speaks about Krishna and the Cow @ 55:30 as a myth and it does appear that his understanding is pretty superficial at this point of time. There is plenty of historical, practical and even archaeological evidence to state that these are not myths (btw, myth comes from mithya - falsehood in Sanskrit). In any case, Americans and the meat eating world needs to wake up to this sordid chapter of Human history and get back on its track of evolving itself.The primary purpose of all consciousness that pervades all life and non-living things is to unite with the source consciousness. That is the integral aim of Yoga (sanskrit for union, union with the innate and immanent divine), a cornerstone of the Hindu philosophy.

author: @lifeofliberty
processed_text: 40:36 - "none of us came make our lives totally green" - not true.¬† You can if you WANT to. But that is exactly the whole point and problem. None of us WANT to. But to say that we CAN'T is a lie.¬† We could if we wanted to, which would entail strictly living on the land and using NO fossil energy of any kind or downstream inputs. But nobody is even willing to entertain this concept or discuss it. So we're left with endless proposals all involving "compromise" (of the lifestyles we REFUSE to give up - even though it is very clear now that these lifestyles will kill the planet and humanity).The other outcome of these endless compromises is that like alternative energy, they won't work (solve the problem) or save the species (humanity) from extinction. Even with conservation, planting trees and making massive energy reductions, this will not change the outcome as suggested (too late now, the effects of climate change will be catastrophic leading to massive levels of starvation and the loss of the biosphere). The resulting die-off is inevitable now.It is the refusal to give up on this civilization and all its accompanying "benefits" that will continue to defeat any efforts at preservation (sustainability of the biosphere, for all life forms). The fault is not money, not really even "greed" (as I long thought), but the basic human nature that seeks comfort and pleasure (at any price, even we are aware it is killing us). Technology leveraged this ability on a massive scale (and hid the effects caused) and we are loathe to turn "back" to a tribal lifestyle that WAS green (yes, they consumed too - but only on limited, local, replenishable levels).That's why 40,000 generations "survived" (didn't go extinct - they're lifestyle was sustainable). But our "civilization" is a disaster and will not survive even 2000 years (or 250 years of advanced technology).These talks are interesting, but still fail to address the truth (heart) of the problem.

author: @Heatfarmer
processed_text: I remember the impact the music,the sound, the energy, the look and artwork of the Sex Pistols had on me in 1977 when my older brother brought 3 of their singles home from England in 1977. I was 9 yrs, but was grown up on all the great stuff, thanks to my brother. Hendrix, CCR, Deep Purple, Black Sabbath, Led Zeppelin, Bowie, Lou Reed, T. Rex, Queen, Alice Cooper (band), The Sweet, Slade, and of course the 60s great bands the Who, the Beatles and the Rolling Stones. None of them, and i mean NONE of them had prepared me for this band and i just immediately knew, that i had found the first band that i could truly relate to. You either hated it or loved it! It was not punk, it was beyond that!And boy, even if they weren't supergroup musicians, what they did was worth 10 times more in terms of artistic value!This was pure Rock n' Roll, like the Rolling Stones, the Who and Hendrix had been in the 60's, and i think its perfect that they didn't do another album, cause i don't know how they possibly could ever improve on Never Mind the Bollocks!

author: @killachunes2349
processed_text: Steve Jones' quote, "We're not into music, we're into chaos" appeared in one of the earliest reviews of a Sex Pistols gig in the NME in 1976. ¬†I remember reading it and being very impressed. ¬†I was the same age as the Pistols and was interested in what was generally known back then, if known at all, as rock music made by punks, though no-one called it Punk Rock. ¬†This interest had been engendered by writers at the NME, especially Nick Kent, who had written big article on Iggy Pop, and Charles Shaar Murray who was commenting on the New York punk scene. ¬†By the start of 1976 I already had Raw Power, The Ramones and Patti Smith's Horses. ¬†I remember thinking that the few pictures I had seen of Johnny Rotten looked promising, but the deal was sealed when I saw the band and some of the other early punks on a programme made by Janet Street-Porter on London Weekend Television. ¬†Steve struggles to answer the interviewers question regarding the bands success in terms of their impact and influence. ¬†The music that he and the rest of the band made was tough, hard rock. Not particularly original, as he attests, but certainly of a type thin on the ground by then. The clincher was the character, style and attitude of Johnny Rotten, he made all the difference.¬†

processed_text: Yep, common sense... that's why most people don't naturally meditate and even when they get interested in meditation, they find it difficult to keep a consistent routine: because it's common sense! It's not common sense and it's not that easy, either, depending on how muddled your mind is. Next time you feel like you're accomplishing a lot of stuff and feeling pretty good about yourself, think of the phrase "don't just do something, sit there" ...and then follow that advice. Don't get high, don't listen to music, don't drink or take a little pill to make the sitting easier. Just sit there and shut up for an hour doing nothing but paying attention to your breath. That is not a common sense behavior, it runs opposite to all our habitual predilections and distractions.

author: @AugustHawk
processed_text: I didn't perceive Andrew as condescending, but rather comparing his specific experience to a more general experience and conveying how he would hike a hypothetical trip. I think he intends hikers to take from this what they need and to advise folks who may want to transition to extreme distance hiking. (39:09)¬†Personally, I wear a pair of Merrell flexible support¬† waterproof hiking boots that weight in 23 oz a pair. I prefer the waterproof because many-a-time I've slipped on a rock in a shallow stream and was glad my foot came up dry or have hiked in¬† the rain and my feet stayed dry - gaiters work with boots too. I simply carry one extra pair of socks and make it a point to change my socks 3x during the hike - we all stop at points along the trail - to avoid sweat build up. Also, I need the little extra support that a boot affords me. One simply needs to define one's needs for hiking and develop the most efficient method for those needs. As for Andrew making money for his trips and advice - that's fine too. This Youtube vid didn't cost me a cent, but I understand the sacrifice, time, and effort Anndrew needed to glean this degree of expertise - much like the Renaissance painters who needed a patron to support them as they created their masterpieces - Andrew too has too earn a living as he forges his skill into a hiking profession. And to all you who donate your time for free - as I do - to teach others about hiking/backpacking... KUDOS and well¬† done. We've all found our niche . God bless.

author: @ajcfactor
processed_text: An impressive athlete, but off base on a lot of this advice. I've never had an issue with gore-tex type material soaking through, although I agree that it's breathability is over stated. Forego the GPS for a map a compass, but then lug around a spot and phone? Carry a GPS and map/compass if you really want to be safe, or just the GPS if you can live with a small amount of risk. And the spot is known to be unreliable as a rescue device because of it's weak transmit signal, plus it requires an expensive subscription. The ResQLink is a far better device. But what I don't agree with the most is the whole concept of spending all this time in incredible places, but then being concerned only with getting through them as fast as possible. Talk about missing the point. If covering the most ground as fast as possible for bragging rights is the priority, run a marathon in the city. A lot less logistics involved, and your view will be the same; the top of your shoes.

author: @alexbouchard4602
processed_text: This is wrong on so many levels! I can't believe he advertised sleeping on a fresh bed of moss. That destroys important habitat that won't recover for hundreds of years.¬†

author: @johnbenbrowning
processed_text: Citation? From what I've been able to find online and from my own experience moss seems to be very hardy relative to typical lawn grasses and can take their fair share of traffic. Keep in mind he mentioned specifically looking for low traffic areas to bed down. Given favorable growing conditions they are considered difficult "weeds" to rid lawns of. What other levels is this wrong on? Most of what he discussed seemed to speak directly to my own backpacking experiences.

author: @alexbouchard4602
processed_text: Ben Browning¬†Moss is way more comfortable but it recovers rarely from being trampled. The reality is that you should always use the designated camping sites, they are put in place in order to protect the environment and it's surrounding. It may not be as pretty or as comfortable but it allows for plants and flowers to grow unperturbed. I think its a small price to pay. I just think that it is not something he should advocate "as the right way". My earlier comment was a little harsh but I work for Parks Canada and I see tourist all the time who gets tips like this on the internet and don't listen to our instructions to stay off the moss. In the Yukon the moss is not hardy at all. Any ways that was my two cents.¬†

author: @johnbenbrowning
processed_text: Alex Bouchard¬†That makes sense, I suppose I gave him the benefit of the doubt in assuming moss was added as an afterthought without considering that a majority of viewers would be applying that particular advice in high hiker volume areas. Interesting that the varieties in northern latitudes are delicate, maybe a function of slow growth rate due to climatic conditions? I've been wanting to make one of those moss bathmats for my shower so I hope there are more rugged varieties. Thanks for responding! I'm envious of my idealized version of your job and lifestyle, I know it's probably not all fun and untouched wilderness, but it's hard to beat that office.

author: @odontomatix
processed_text: I once was on top of Pike's Peak, Colorado, on a car trip and I got out at a vista point, but it was drizzling so I opened an umbrella which had a pointed metal tip like a trekking pole. ¬†As I stood there, I suddenly realized I was in effect holding a lightning rod on top of a mountain in a potential thunderstorm. ¬†I think I may even have heard some static electricity crackles above the umbrella. Duh! ¬†If lightning hit, where do you think it would first be attracted?! ¬†That umbrella immediately went back into the car, and so did I! ¬†Also, umbrellas are easily destroyed, turned inside out, in a wind gust. ¬†So, forget the umbrella.

author: @stepheng6497
processed_text: What do you suppose is meant by the words "sound doctrine"?¬† When the suggestion is made to follow sound doctrine, and not to follow whatever sounds good to your desires or "lusts" as it it put, I see that what is being called for is understanding.¬† A doctrine can only be seen as sound if it can be examined and understood as correct.¬† Something can only be understood as correct and reasonable (in other words, "sound") if it is in agreement with a person's experience.¬† But then you go and say that Jesus Christ is the Lord and the only way to Salvation.¬† This is something that no one can see as sound doctrine because it is something that is not able to be reasoned by personal experience.¬† You are attempting to make your point in exactly the way your quote is arguing against. You are also degrading Christ by making him seem magical.¬† I believe that Jesus' doctrine was sound doctrine. Christ saw the ways in which the experience of the world could be used positively for achieving the utmost result of living in it.¬† But you should see here that the ways are there for everyone - they exist as part of the world, part of humanity.¬† The experience of life which leads to an individual's salvation, or what could possibly be the same thing as the word "enlightenment", was something that Christ showed people.¬† Following him lead to salvation BECAUSE he could show you truths about the world - but those truths are part of the world with or without him.¬† You degrade Christ further by implying that the things he taught people to do have no effect.¬† How do I come to this conclusion?¬† If the instructions have no effect unless they have Christ behind them saying them, then they have no effect by themselves. In other words you deny sound doctrine.¬† If Christ tells people that eating a cheeseburger gets you to heaven, then its safe to say that even if you ate a cheeseburger before he was around then you got to heaven.¬† To use a weird metaphor.¬† He never said that he was MAKING things true, he stated truths, simply. You degrade Christ further again by implying that no one can understand his teaching fully enough to teach enlightenment or show the way to salvation in their own words.¬† That would make him the world's worst teacher.¬† You degrade him by implying that the truths he was teaching aren't real enough for people to discover for themselves and teach as they have discovered them.¬† That would make him magical, and his teachings not truths about the world and about people in the world - but an invention.¬† Christ, like modern teachers with whom I include Tolle, SHOW the way, with sound doctrine, reason, and an appeal to actual understanding that the way is already there as something to be discovered.¬† They do not create or INVENT a way.¬† To invent a way is a fable.¬† Reread your quote from Timothy and go more deeply into it.

author: @nthperson
processed_text: The Founding Father who best understood the principles of a just political economy was Thomas Paine. Paine was influenced by Smith and Turgot, who detailed the destructive character of the system of land tenure of the Old World, a system essentially carried over into the New World. In "Agrarian Justice," Paine asserted that the owners of land owed to society a ground rent for the privilege. In most of the world for most of history, as observed by Smith, Turgot and (later) Henry George, the rents were privatized which caused land to come to have a selling price. As the selling price of land rose, so did the necessity for most purchasers of land to do so with credit at interest.

Though, Cobb tells Saito that he will likely not remember that they even had an arrangement once he awakes from Limbo. I suppose since Cobb was the one who pulls him out of Limbo (thus triggering memories of how he knew Cobb), that is how Saito still remembers the arrangement upon waking up on the plane.

author: @gamma3c
processed_text: @5:25 He makes the correct assumption about mass media inceptions, and then he doesn't see what this movie does! It incepts the idea that reality may be "a dream"? The Matrix already did that. In this movie performing inception involves: developing drugs, buying airlines, going into war-like scenes on five different dream layers with lots of explosions and falling vans and other extreme things happening - just in order to put one idea in one man's head. Prof. Johnson implies that commercials (~10 sec long) do inception on millions of people, and yet, he can't see the contradiction here! Inception is a movie that does inception on millions of people planting this idea: inception is really hard (borderline impossible) to do! So you don't have to be alert, don't need to protect yourselves, don't have to "militarize" your subconscious.... That's the real purpose. First they propose it in the helicopter scene, and then, with the actual inception mission, they "prove" it to you - that is, convince you by turning off your rational mind with plot holes and sensory overload (something Hollywood movies do a lot).Another thing he missed was character transference. This time, not by the hero - but by Saito. Notice how many resonances this movie has with The Last Samurai. The hero is troubled, away from home (USA), wrecked with guilt and regret, has trouble sleeping (nightmares about the past that haunts him) and then Watanabe's character shows up and offers redemption in some way. The hero is initially W's adversary but later becomes recruited by him and his cause. W is powerful and confident, and his goal is to convince a very powerful but young and inexperienced man to change his mind about a decision of vast importance regarding leadership (something he has inherited). Notice that Hans Zimmer composed the music (something that vastly contributes to the "air") of both movies. And then prof. Johnson says that Mal being played by an actress who played Piaf in a previous movie is a coincidence? Come on...Cobb definitely regrets the inception he did on Mal - she's the one who "doesn't regret nothing at all", because she's certain about her (ghostly?) agenda. Character transference! Learn these two magic words, Hollywood does it all the time!(One screaming example would be Keanu Reeves: Little Buddha + Johnny Mnemonic = The Matrix. In terms of characters, of course, and only to a certain extent.)

this 'seemingly improbable' flight, is the battle.The deeper you go and the more layers you peel off and stare down, the faster your progress time will go, asrepresented by the speed of time the more dreams then went within the dreams. ¬†¬†Cobb's wife represented guilt. ¬†Guilt wrapped in a beautiful layer, with the strongest emotions attached like love,¬†the shared creation of children, and the guilt that his wanting to control her contributed to her decision to end her life.¬†And that's just one emotion, wrapped up in so many layers, seemingly impossible to break all combinations. ¬†But that's what we all have to face to then channel the supreme creative force into our lives. ¬†You don't have toovercome it all at once, but you have to surrender to this ultimate battle and start the war. ¬†Limbo is what happens when you give up in the middle of the battle. ¬†You get lost in whatever world you currently¬†chose to die and slowly decay and who knows how long it will take to wake up.¬†This movie is Cobb's limbo. ¬†He was lost, he had given up to the temptation of Guilt's wrath many times. ¬†When Cobb woke up on the plane that look on his face is, wow, I can't believe I made it and how much I¬†went through to let that guilt go. ¬†The banishment of USA just meant Cobb wouldn't allow himself to go back because of guilt. ¬†Once the¬†opportunity offered itself and he was ready also started--even if it may not show that.¬†The point is not that the movie inception was a dream, but that what we call reality is a dream, and therefore, probablya dream within a dream--multiplied author: @bluo88
processed_text: @Jon TysonIt's true that income producing investments (call this IPI) have a tax advantage in a Roth type retirement account, but you ultimately need to consider your investment objectives and alternatives. For example, age is a very important factor. If you're young, you'd probably benefit more in the long run from funds which seek aggressive capital growth (e.g. small and mid cap funds) than from funds which focus on IPI. Thus, you might choose not to have any retirement money in IPI until you're much closer to retirement and need to reduce risk. At the same time, it could make sense to have IPI in your non-retirement account to diversify/reduce volatility and if you plan to use the money for things before retirement.

author: @Razyre
processed_text: Why... nobody should be texting on their watch, using the internet on their watch etc... Unless you can do it with voice, then don't. This is slow and counter intuitive. Just get your damned phone out of your pocket. Calling on a watch makes sense, texting and typing in general does not.

author: @spider853
processed_text: Is it bad if you can text and call on both?I bet you would say the same a few years ago... why type on a phone if you have a laptop/notebook.

author: @Razyre
processed_text: Yes, yes it is.It's ridiculous. It's 1.5" touchscreen. You can barely fit a single finger on the display. Just because you /can/ do something doesn't mean you should.With new devices like this people need to escape the gimmicks and focus on what's useful.Accurate voice controlled messaging from a watch, makes sense. Calling from a watch, makes sense. It's a natural interface and it's a sensible extension from your phone. The microphone is in place without you having to move a muscle.Having said this, even then you can have earphones with an inline mic to do the same job.Where smart watches excel are notifications and telling the time. Until the format changes they won't be practical for anything more.

author: @Razyre
processed_text: *****¬†Voice controls are vastly better than they used to be and improving all the time. Google Now is in fact very good. It is up to the manufacturer to choose the correct sort of microphone to hear you from range and this is what we should be seeing with the Apple Watch.When you call someone they can hear at least half of your conversation anyway. If you want to have privacy, text on your phone, exactly as I suggested.I'm simply proposing sensible ways for you to communicate on a smartwatch, not with a silly keyboard like this. This technology is a waste of time, perfecting voice is far more interesting.

processed_text: I like Star Trek TNG and the holodeck but this is just too far off from that. Simply put that room was a huge empty space that would create solid light object that people could interact with. This are just projections on the wall... I could just take out my TV, clear the space around him, buy a project and hook my PC/console to it and get the same result w/o buying 6 kinects, 5 other projectors, ceiling structure and hire a team to put the whole contraption in place. Also the games shown are just poor :(Now I mean no disrespect by what I said. Right now from what I've seen I'm convinced that this is the wrong approach towards turning your living room into a live holodeck. Among the problems presented is the fact that 1 single kinect unit isn't actually capable of correctly recording player movement at high speeds. The whole cost of this would be too impractical and the size is another problem. Also it doesn't help to show hastily put together software.I think right now VR head-sets are much cheaper and comfortable. Maybe update Kinect so it works a bit better (or provide gloves/sneakers that will help with motion tracking) and add a VR head-set so you can really go into the game world for full immersion.

author: @Shadowcam00
processed_text: Finally! We can play awkward and basic games on the walls and floor for only the cost of several expensive projectors and the equipment required to set them up and run the programs. YAY!All sarcasm aside, using a bunch of projectors like this just isn't the way to go. Projector technology isn't heading anywhere that could make this viable anytime soon.(or at all when you take into account the high expenses) I can see this being used for things like an arcade-like attraction in a theme-part or museum, but realistically, no one will be making content for this kind of thing due to the costs and complexity. The best gaming innovations in the near-to-mid future will be a combination of virtual reality and augmented reality implementations; That's because people CAN adapt that technology to increasingly complex and impressive uses in the near future, while keeping costs relatively low for both businesses and regular consumers.

author: @GiuseppeGaetanoSabatelli
processed_text: It's a proof of concept. This technology could be used only for training programs, technology stores, businesses, who knows. Just because it uses expensive equipment doesn't mean "this just isn't the way to go."You need to start with something.

author: @Shadowcam00
processed_text: This would have been cool as a proof of concept 10 years ago. But now, the thought of using thousands of dollars worth of equipment for these lackluster results is just not impressive. Like i said, this sort of thing could have uses in theme-parks or someplace where the people using it could afford to develop their own content, but not much beyond that. There's simply not that much room for this thing to be further innovated in a way that makes it catch on anytime soon. Virtual reality and augmented reality, however, are seeing rapid innovations that are drastically improving their capabilities while still keeping them somewhat affordable to average consumers.

author: @Shadowcam00
processed_text: SurphyseIf you can see a projector setup like this becoming cheap in the near future, you're mistaken. Imagine for a moment how much a setup with half a dozen HD projectors equipped with special censors will cost to instal and maintain; not even a gradual reduction in price due to efficiency of manufacturing will make that affordable for quite a while. Then there's the problem of content; if 3D-TVs haven't fully caught on yet due to lack of content, this will have the same problem magnified by 10; no one will want to make content for such a limited and complicated use besides the people who can afford to develop it in-house. And turning your room into Tony Stark's workshop? Maybe, but then all you'll be able to do there is play minigames, which won't exactly shake up the gaming landscape. Virtual and augmented reality can have an impact on the gaming landscape in the near future and stay relatively affordable, while this projector setup will do neither.

author: @kestonkende
processed_text: You can't predict the market in 5-10 years, the prices of the materials, the profit margins. We don't know. This implementation can be the gateway to something greater. Everyone's watching this at face value but prototypes like this help introduce ideas that can be used by the general consumer later in the future.

author: @Haaklong
processed_text: Microsoft Research¬†Dear Microsoft Research,Though personally I download all your applications on Windows Phone, Google Android, and my Windows P.C. and I like all the innovations coming out of the Nokia Beta Labs and see that the innovations Microsoft puts up are world-changing, personally I hope that Microsoft will release more beta variants of their software to the public so your services can be tested in regular and realistic environments and Microsoft can see potential problems earlier rather than later.This is why Google is so successful, they place their technology in the hands of the users, even if it's only half-baked so they can collect more data and learn from what goes both wrong and right, Apple fails to innovate 'cause they're so secretive, I most sincerely hope that Microsoft won't take ''the Apple way'' and will be more interactive, though news outlets love ''mysterious'' and ''secret'' things, Microsoft shouldn't be a cult, Microsoft should invite as many people as possible to help and improve the best software in the world.Yours most sincerely and faithfully,Haaklong

author: @chadvoller
processed_text: Playing with it right now, and it seems to know pretty much any word I try to swipe in. All swiping keyboards are predictive, that's part of the algorithm. As long as you go through the letters, it can narrow down what you are trying to type, as you go. And if there are multiple possibilities, they show up as suggestions above. For instance, I can swipe dictionary, thesaurus, tyrannosaurus, elevator, fantastic, Beelzebub, alchemy... it has figured everyone one of those out without fail. There are words that it can't get, that are not often used in texts. Like genetical, but that fails spell check for YouTube as well. But it has to be setup for every language. This wouldn't work in Spanish, German, Yiddish, etc, until those are supported, and have to be set as your language. I get it that this looks too good to be true. If you can find someone with the developers preview, try it out. This swiping is done insanely well. Sometimes freakishly.

author: @MaitreyaVyas
processed_text: As a MS lover I love this Socl network! :)¬†

At first I thought of this as another sensory gimmick, but now I think about it more, this can really aid game-play. If an important bit of informations starts to move out of the screen area you can still track it in your peripheral vision, like having triple screens but maybe better.Think about a racing game while in the driver's seat, another driver thats coming from behind and is now about to cross your side in your TV blindspot, you can now be aware of the car and avoid collision.¬†Or enemy radar in an FPS, as a powerup could allow you to see enemies before they cross into your screen area. Or you could better know your ally is at your side, literally.¬†Then there is the sheer effects, it could essentially display and image of your living room, over your living room, and then Photoshop effects that relate to the game, like blood spatter.¬†Or you could go for the 3D effect, and have projectiles come toward you running from the TV down the furniture and across the floor at you, and all of this is compensating for the angles of your physical area to still produce straight lines and things like that using the camera.¬†I like it!

author: @d0nkatron
processed_text: Even if the input were to catch up with the refresh rate of our current panels we would be at 16.6ms for the majority of screens (60hz) and just under 7ms for 144hz displays. This is how long it takes for the next frame of the image to come up since the last. 7ms aint bad at all tho lol. Soon we'll have 288hz or around that figure which will be about 4ms. The law of diminishing returns with our technology growth means that 1ms is quite a ways from now unless a new display technology altogether is developed before then. Then we still have to conquer the bigger beast of input latency.¬†
